"2020-06-08 11:38:01","menu_order":0,"mime_type":"image\/jpeg","type":"image","subtype":"jpeg","icon":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-includes\/images\/media\/default.png","width":460,"height":316,"sizes":{"thumbnail":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/09\/Bound-with-bright-beatiful-things_Picard-150x150.jpg","thumbnail-width":150,"thumbnail-height":150,"medium":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/09\/Bound-with-bright-beatiful-things_Picard-300x206.jpg","medium-width":300,"medium-height":206,"medium_large":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/09\/Bound-with-bright-beatiful-things_Picard.jpg","medium_large-width":460,"medium_large-height":316,"large":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/09\/Bound-with-bright-beatiful-things_Picard.jpg","large-width":460,"large-height":316,"1536x1536":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/09\/Bound-with-bright-beatiful-things_Picard.jpg","1536x1536-width":460,"1536x1536-height":316,"2048x2048":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/09\/Bound-with-bright-beatiful-things_Picard.jpg","2048x2048-width":460,"2048x2048-height":316,"tiny-preview":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/09\/Bound-with-bright-beatiful-things_Picard-48x48.jpg","tiny-preview-width":48,"tiny-preview-height":48,"feature":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/09\/Bound-with-bright-beatiful-things_Picard.jpg","feature-width":460,"feature-height":316}}]},{"acf_fc_layout":"text","text":"<p>There is always a time before, the second \/ minute \/ hour \/ day \/ week \/ month \/ year before, a preceding generation, an older dynasty. Each human occasion is locked within a larger suite where instants fall on the page of our collective and singular imaginations like notes on a score. We acknowledge a darker, deeper time from which we must have emerged\u2014the stuff of myth, divination, philosophy, and theory. Adam Smith drew hunters and shepherds from this amorphous past to produce a theory of capital and society in <em>The Wealth of Nations<\/em>. Archaeologists unearth artifacts in anthropological digs with parallel intensity, puzzling over the teeth of Neanderthals where isotopes in dental plaque reveal traces of raw aspirin and Penicillium.<span class=\"annotation\"><span class=\"annotation-target\"><\/span><span class=\"relative\"><span class=\"annotation-ring\"><\/span><\/span><span class=\"annotation-counter annotation-counter-inner\"><\/span><span class=\"annotation-content hidden xl:inline leading-tight\"><span class=\"annotation-counter annotation-counter-outer\"><\/span>University of Adelaide, &#8220;Dental plaque DNA shows Neanderthals used \u2018aspirin\u2019,\u201d <em>ScienceDaily<\/em>, 8 March 2017, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.sciencedaily.com\/releases\/2017\/03\/170308131218.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">online<\/a>.<\/span><\/span> Or the virtual, scientific models\u2014studies and projections that aim to uncover a point of origin (a bang for instance) after which life began and then diversified. Yet rather than lock this point of geologic departure in time, the world instead recedes into the past of human knowledge, growing exponentially older as scientific tools become more sophisticated.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p><em>Extract from Caroline Picard, &#8220;Bound with Bright Beautiful Things,\u201d Deep Time Chicago Pamphlet Series, 2017.<\/em><\/p>\n"},{"acf_fc_layout":"pdf","display":"spreadsWithCover","pdf":{"ID":26382,"id":26382,"title":"Caroline Picard_Bound with Bright Beautiful Things","filename":"Caroline-Picard_Bound-with-Bright-Beautiful-Things.pdf","filesize":460268,"url":"https:\/\/content.anthropocene-curriculum.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2017\/04\/Caroline-Picard_Bound-with-Bright-Be